Date: Thu, 04 Dec 1997 23:53:08 -0500
From: Jack Woodall, Ph.D. <woodall@wadsworth.org>

On November 29, 1997, Kevin Gillespie wrote [(04) message cited above:
"The Great Plains grasslands in USA [are home for ground squirrels (e.g.,
_Citellus_) and prairie dogs (e.g., _Cynomys_). Are there any equivalents
in Mongolia?"
Yes, the Mongolian marmot is the local equivalent of the North American
prairie dog, which is also known as ground hog and woodchuck. Like its
cousin in the American West, the Mongolian marmot carries plague, which a
few marmot hunters suffer from every year.
--
Jack Woodall, Ph.D., Director, ProMED-mail
