[2
Date: Fri, 05 Dec 1997 14:43:09 -0700
From: Charles H. Calisher <calisher@usa.healthnet.org>

According to "Walker's Mammals of the World" Fifth Edition, Volume I (R.<.
Nowak, editor): There is considerable disagreement about the systematics of
Marmota in Eurasia, with some authorities recognizing only three species
and others as many as eight. There are:
_M. camtschatica_: mountains of northeastern Siberia from Lake Baikal to
Kamchatka
_M. bobak_ [also considered as species distinct from _M. bobak_ are _M.
baibacina_ (Central Asia, Sinkiang, and Mongolia); _M. himalayana_
(Himalayan region); and _M. sibirica_ (southern Siberia, Mongolia, northern
China): Poland and Romania to Manchuria and central China (This might be
the one Jack's thinking of.)
_M. caudata_: mountains of central Asia
_M. menzbieri_: Tien Shan Mountains of Uzbekistan and southeastern Kazakhistan
Hibernation burrows may be 5-7 m deep and tunnels 10-70 m long, or even 113
m in the case of _M. camtschatica_. Must be cold there.
--
Charles H. Calisher, Ph.D.
